{"title_page": "Siddiq Baloch", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Siddiq Baloch\n| image = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1940|2|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Lyari]], [[Karachi]], [[British India]] (now in [[Pakistan]])\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2018|2|5|1940|2|10}}\n| death_place = [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]]\n| occupation = [[Politician]], [[Journalist]]\n| title =''[[Dawn newspaper|DAWN]]''\n}}\n\n'''Siddiq Baloch''' (alternatively '''Siddiq Balouch''' or '''Siddique Baloch''') (10 February 1940<ref>http://balochwarna.com/2018/02/06/balochistan-veteran-journalist-siddique-baloch-passes-away/</ref> \u2013 5 February 2018)<ref>https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/02/06/siddiq-baloch-passes-away-in-karachi/</ref> was a [[Pakistan]]i English-language journalist, and senior political economist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1387669|title=Veteran journalist Siddique Baloch passes away in Karachi|last=Ali|first=Syed Ali Shah {{!}} Imtiaz|date=2018-02-06|work=DAWN.COM|access-date=2018-02-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHe was Editor-in-chief of the English daily ''Balochistan Express'' ([[Quetta]]), ''The Guardian'' ([[Karachi]]) an Urdu daily ''Azadi'', and the ''English Weekly Express'', ([[Quetta]]). He also regularly contributed columns to [[Dawn newspaper|''Dawn'']], and was an authority on Balochistan's social, political and economic matters.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nBalouch was born in the suburb of [[Lyari]], in Pakistan's 'business capital' [[Karachi]], but migrated to [[Quetta]], [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]] in 1990.<ref name=\"Feeling of alienation of Baloch youth irreversible\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=171626\n|title=' 'Feeling of alienation of Baloch youth irreversible'' \u2013 The News April 10, 2009\n|publisher=www.thenews.com.pk\n|accessdate=\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref>\n\nHe was a staunch believer in the 'freedom of expression' and, over the years, has spoken openly against dictatorship and bans on the media. When the [[Pakistan Electronic Media Regulatory Authority]] (PEMRA) Ordinance was amended in November 2007 by President [[Pervez Musharraf]], placing curbs on the media, Balouch told ''Weekly Pulse'':<blockquote>\n\"PEMRA ordinance is a bid to muffle the right to freedom of expression and voice of truth. But this voice cannot be stifled in the present age. All the steps being taken by the incumbent unconstitutional and illegal rulers are alien to constitution. The way the media and civil society members are raising voice against it is laudable.\"<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.weeklypulse.org/pulse/article/963.html\n|title=' 'Press Freedom' \u2013 By Special Report\n|publisher=www.weeklypulse.org\n|accessdate=\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nHe followed the religion of [[Islam]], and was thus a [[Muslim]].\n\n==Education==\n\nBalouch acquired his primary education from a neighbourhood school in [[Karachi]]. He sat his Matriculation examination from the famous Sindh Madrasatul Islam School, in 1959.<ref name=\"Feeling of alienation of Baloch youth irreversible\"/> He joined SM College in 1961, from where he graduated in 1964.\n\nBalouch had a master's degree in Economics, which he was awarded in 1966 from the University of Karachi.\n\n==Politics==\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Siddiqbalocharticle.jpg|thumb|left|An article on Siddiq Baloch in ''The News''.]] -->Balouch took an active part in politics from an early age. As a student, he was elected as the President of the Students' Union at the SM College from 1963\u20131964.<ref name=\"Siddiq Baloch - The News\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=171626\n|title=' 'Siqqid Baloch'' \u2013 The News April 10, 2009\n|publisher=www.thenews.com.pk\n|accessdate=\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref>\n\nHe had been an active member of the left-wing National Students Federation [NSF], and participated in the Anti-One Unit movement, as well as a campaign against three-year degree courses. He was also one of the founding members of the Baloch Students Organization [BSO], when it was established in 1962, and became its senior vice president in 1966.<ref name=\"Siddiq Baloch - The News\"/>\n\nBalouch was affiliated with the National Awami Party [NAP] and served as Press Secretary to NAP's Ghouse Bux Bizenjo, the then Governor of Balochistan, for four months, between 1972 \u2013 1973. When the NAP government was dismissed by President [[Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto]] on the alleged charge of implication in the infamous Hyderabad Conspiracy, Balouch was jailed for five years, and released only when Bhutto's government was overthrown by General [[Zia ul Haq]].\n<ref name=\"Siddiq Baloch - The News\"/>\n\nIn August 2008, he accompanied [[Syed Yousaf Raza Gillani|Prime Minister Gillani]] on a three-day visit to Sri Lanka.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.na.gov.pk/questions/session8/thursday201108_8S.pdf\n|title=' National Assembly Secretariat (8th Session) \u2013 Questions for oral answers, and their replies\n|publisher=www.na.gov.pk\n|accessdate=\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] (PPP) government returned to power in February 2008, Balouch was among the leaders who welcomed it, chiefly because new President Asif Ali Zardari was a Baloch, and he had 'defeated a dictator with his political might.'<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.unpo.org/content/view/8620/236/\n|title=' Balochistan: Leaders Welcome Zardari\n|publisher=www.unpo.org\n|accessdate=\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref>\nHowever, he also said that the challenges ahead for the PPP in Balochistan were tough, and that a complete end to military operation and provision of space to all political stakeholders was the only real solution.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/india-news/baloch-leaders-hope-zardaris-election-as-pak-president-will-end-their-woes_10093114.html\n|title=' Baloch leaders hope Zardaris election as Pak President will end their woes\n|publisher=www.thaindian.com\n|accessdate=\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Journalism==\n\nMr. Balouch joined Pakistan's oldest and most widely circulated newspaper, ''Dawn'', as its sub-editor in 1966, and worked there in different capacities for 28 years.\n\nIn 1981, he was elected as President of the Karachi Union of Journalists [KJU]. He took an active part in the freedom of expression movement, and served two terms. He was also elected as President of the Balochistan Newspapers Editors Council, and as a Vice-President of the Karachi Press Club.\n\nOver the years, Balouch had written for the ''Daily Balochistan Express,''<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.internews.org.pk/pNewsDetail.php?NewsID=9\n|title=Legal and Political Reporting Training \u2013 Stipends Stories\n|publisher=www.internews.org.pk\n|accessdate=\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref> and also served the Council of Pakistan Newspapers Editors [CPNE] as its Balochistan Vice President.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.onlinenews.com.pk/details.php?id=136490\n|title=Siddiq Balouch elected as CPNE Balouchistan Vice President\n|publisher=www.onlinenews.com.pk\n|accessdate=\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref>\n\nHe is one of the most widely quoted journalists by the Pakistani and International media on Balochistan-related issues. He had extensively travelled as a part of his journalistic activities.\n\nHe was the editor of the ''Balochistan Express,'' and publishes an Urdu paper called ''Azadi'' [Liberty].<ref name=\"Feeling of alienation of Baloch youth irreversible\"/>\n\n==As an author==\n\nBalouch had authored a book on the politics and economy of [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]], titled ''A Critical Comment on the Political Economy of Balochistan'',<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=https://openlibrary.org/b/OL3722374M/critical-comment-on-political-economy-of-Balochistan\n|title=A critical comment on political economy of Balochistan \u2013 By Siddiq Baloch\n|via=[[Open Library]]\n|accessdate=2008-03-27\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref> which was released in January 2004, in a ceremony organised by literary organisation, Daira.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.dawn.com/2004/01/08/nat27.htm\n|title='Balochistan needs more attention' -DAWN \u2013 National\n|date=8 January 2004\n|publisher=www.dawn.com\n|accessdate=2008-03-27\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baloch, Siddiq}}\n[[Category:Pakistani male journalists|Baluch, Siddiq]]\n[[Category:People from Quetta]]\n[[Category:University of Karachi alumni]]\n[[Category:Baloch journalists]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Dawn (newspaper) people]]\n[[Category:People from Lyari Town]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Siddiq Baloch\n| image = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1940|2|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Lyari]], [[Karachi]], [[British India]] (now in [[Pakistan]])\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2018|2|5|1940|2|10}}\n| death_place = [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]]\n| occupation = [[Politician]], [[Journalist]]\n| title =''[[Dawn newspaper|DAWN]]''\n}}\n\n'''Siddiq Baloch''' (alternatively '''Siddiq Balouch''' or '''Siddique Baloch''') (10 February 1940<ref>http://balochwarna.com/2018/02/06/balochistan-veteran-journalist-siddique-baloch-passes-away/</ref> \u2013 5 February 2018)<ref>https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/02/06/siddiq-baloch-passes-away-in-karachi/</ref> was a [[Pakistan]]i English-language journalist, and senior political economist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1387669|title=Veteran journalist Siddique Baloch passes away in Karachi|last=Ali|first=Syed Ali Shah {{!}} Imtiaz|date=2018-02-06|work=DAWN.COM|access-date=2018-02-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHe was Editor-in-chief of the English daily ''Balochistan Express'' ([[Quetta]]), ''The Guardian'' ([[Karachi]]) an Urdu daily ''Azadi'', and the ''English Weekly Express'', ([[Quetta]]). He also regularly contributed columns to [[Dawn newspaper|''Dawn'']], and was an authority on Balochistan's social, political and economic matters.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nBalouch was born in the suburb of [[Lyari]], in Pakistan's 'business capital' [[Karachi]], but migrated to [[Quetta]], [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]] in 1990.<ref name=\"Feeling of alienation of Baloch youth irreversible\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=171626\n|title=' 'Feeling of alienation of Baloch youth irreversible'' \u2013 The News April 10, 2009\n|publisher=www.thenews.com.pk\n|accessdate=\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref>\n\nHe was a staunch believer in the 'freedom of expression' and, over the years, has spoken openly against dictatorship and bans on the media. When the [[Pakistan Electronic Media Regulatory Authority]] (PEMRA) Ordinance was amended in November 2007 by President [[Pervez Musharraf]], placing curbs on the media, Balouch told ''Weekly Pulse'':<blockquote>\n\"PEMRA ordinance is a bid to muffle the right to freedom of expression and voice of truth. But this voice cannot be stifled in the present age. All the steps being taken by the incumbent unconstitutional and illegal rulers are alien to constitution. The way the media and civil society members are raising voice against it is laudable.\"<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.weeklypulse.org/pulse/article/963.html\n|title=' 'Press Freedom' \u2013 By Special Report\n|publisher=www.weeklypulse.org\n|accessdate=\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nHe followed the religion of [[Islam]], and was thus a [[Muslim]].\n\n==Education==\n\nBalouch acquired his primary education from a neighbourhood school in [[Karachi]]. He sat his Marticulation examination from the famous Sindh Madrasatul Islam School, in 1959.<ref name=\"Feeling of alienation of Baloch youth irreversible\"/> He joined SM College in 1961, from where he graduated in 1964.\n\nBalouch had a master's degree in Economics, which he was awarded in 1966 from the University of Karachi.\n\n==Politics==\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Siddiqbalocharticle.jpg|thumb|left|An article on Siddiq Baloch in ''The News''.]] -->Balouch took an active part in politics from an early age. As a student, he was elected as the President of the Students' Union at the SM College from 1963\u20131964.<ref name=\"Siddiq Baloch - The News\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=171626\n|title=' 'Siqqid Baloch'' \u2013 The News April 10, 2009\n|publisher=www.thenews.com.pk\n|accessdate=\n|last=\n|first=\n}}\n</ref>\n\nHe had been an active member of the left-wing National Students Federation [NSF], and participated in the Anti-One Unit movement, as well as a campaign against three-year degree courses. He was also one of the founding members of the Baloch Students Organization [BSO], when it was established in 1962, and became its senior vice president in 1966.<ref name=\"Siddiq Baloch - The News\"/>\n\nBalouch was affiliated with the National Awami Party [NAP] and served as Press Secretary to NAP's Ghouse Bux Bizenjo, the then Governor of Balochistan, for four months, between 1972 \u2013 1973. When the NAP government was dismissed by President [[Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto]] on the alleged charge of implication in the infamous Hyderabad Conspiracy, Balouch was jailed for five years, and released only when Bhutto's government was overthrown by General [[Zia ul Haq]].\n<ref name=\"Siddiq Baloch - The News\"/>\n\nIn August 2008, he accompanied [[Syed Yousaf Raza Gillani|Prime Minister Gillani]] on a three-day visit to Sri Lanka.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.na.gov.pk/questions/session8/thursday201108_8S.pdf\n|title=' National Assembly Secretariat (8th Session) \u2013 Questions for oral answers, and their replies\n|publisher=www.n